BVD-CAIRO-STA-001	Unenforced View Function Constraint	Functions decorated with #[view] or marked as view are intended to be read-only and should not modify contract state. However, Cairo compiler doesn't strictly enforce this constraint. If a view function modifies storage or calls non-view external functions, it violates the expected behavior and can lead to unexpected state changes during what should be read-only operations.	state-consistency	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Ensure view functions only read state and never write to storage. Avoid calling external functions from view functions unless those functions are also guaranteed to be view. Use read-only storage access patterns. Consider using @view decorator in Cairo 0 or proper view semantics in Cairo 1/2.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: View function modifying state\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_balance(self: @ContractState, account: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    let balance = self.balances.read(account);\\n    // View function should not write!\\n    self.last_query_time.write(get_block_timestamp());\\n    balance\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Pure read-only view function\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_balance(self: @ContractState, account: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    self.balances.read(account)\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Unenforced View"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch99-01-02-a-simple-contract.html", "title": "Cairo External Functions"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.981491+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.035786+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-QUA-003	Unused Function Arguments	Function parameters that are never used in the function body indicate incomplete implementation, copy-paste errors, or unnecessary complexity. Unused arguments increase gas costs, confuse developers about the function's intent, and may hide bugs where the argument should have been used but wasn't. This is especially problematic in external functions where users pay gas for passing unused data.	code-quality	low	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Remove unused parameters from function signatures. If a parameter might be needed for future compatibility, document why it's currently unused. Consider using _ prefix for intentionally unused parameters. For interface implementations where arguments are required but unused, document the reason clearly.", "code_example": "// PROBLEMATIC: Unused argument\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_config(ref self: ContractState, new_value: u256, timestamp: u64) {\\n    // timestamp parameter is never used\\n    self.config.write(new_value);\\n}\\n\\n// BETTER: Remove unused parameter\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_config(ref self: ContractState, new_value: u256) {\\n    self.config.write(new_value);\\n}\\n\\n// OR: Use underscore prefix if intentionally unused for interface compatibility\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_config(ref self: ContractState, new_value: u256, _reserved: u64) {\\n    // _reserved indicates intentionally unused parameter\\n    self.config.write(new_value);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Unused Arguments"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:26.01321+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.118855+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-LOG-003	Incorrect Exponentiation Logic	Flawed power/exponentiation calculations that can cause overflow, incorrect results, or inefficient computation. Exponentiation in Solana programs must handle potential overflow and use appropriate methods for large numbers.	logic-errors	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use checked_pow() for exponentiation to detect overflow. For large exponents, consider using libraries like num-bigint or implement custom algorithms with overflow detection.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked exponentiation\\npub fn calculate_compound_interest(\\n    principal: u64,\\n    rate: u64,  // Rate in basis points\\n    periods: u32,\\n) -> u64 {\\n    // Can easily overflow!\\n    let multiplier = (10000 + rate).pow(periods);\\n    (principal * multiplier) / 10000_u64.pow(periods)\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: No overflow check\\npub fn calculate_power(base: u64, exp: u32) -> u64 {\\n    base.pow(exp)  // Panics on overflow in debug, wraps in release\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Inefficient repeated multiplication\\npub fn power_iterative(base: u64, exp: u32) -> u64 {\\n    let mut result = 1;\\n    for _ in 0..exp {\\n        result *= base;  // No overflow check, inefficient\\n    }\\n    result\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked exponentiation\\npub fn calculate_power(\\n    base: u64,\\n    exp: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    base.checked_pow(exp)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Compound interest with overflow check\\npub fn calculate_compound_interest(\\n    principal: u64,\\n    rate: u64,\\n    periods: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    const BASIS: u64 = 10000;\\n    \\n    let rate_plus_basis = rate\\n        .checked_add(BASIS)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    let numerator = rate_plus_basis\\n        .checked_pow(periods)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    let denominator = BASIS\\n        .checked_pow(periods)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    principal\\n        .checked_mul(numerator)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(denominator))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Power with reasonable limits\\npub fn safe_power(\\n    base: u64,\\n    exp: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // Limit exponent to prevent overflow\\n    const MAX_EXPONENT: u32 = 64;\\n    \\n    if exp > MAX_EXPONENT {\\n        return Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument);\\n    }\\n    \\n    if base == 0 {\\n        return Ok(0);\\n    }\\n    \\n    if base == 1 {\\n        return Ok(1);\\n    }\\n    \\n    base.checked_pow(exp)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\nconst MAX_SAFE_EXPONENT: u32 = 20;\\n\\npub fn calculate_reward_multiplier(\\n    ctx: Context<CalculateReward>,\\n    base: u64,\\n    exponent: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64> {\\n    require!(\\n        exponent <= MAX_SAFE_EXPONENT,\\n        ErrorCode::ExponentTooLarge\\n    );\\n    \\n    let result = base\\n        .checked_pow(exponent)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(result)\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/primitive.u64.html#method.pow", "https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/primitive.u64.html#method.checked_pow"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.940302+00	2025-11-29 01:51:09.946447+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-INT-006	Integer Multiplication Overflow	Multiplication operations that risk numeric overflow without proper checking. In Solana programs, unchecked multiplication is particularly dangerous as products grow exponentially and can easily exceed u64::MAX. This commonly occurs in token calculations with decimal conversions, fee calculations, and compound interest formulas.	arithmetic	high	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use checked_mul() for all multiplication operations. Be especially careful with token decimal conversions and fee calculations where multiplication is common.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unchecked multiplication\\npub fn convert_tokens(amount: u64, rate: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Can easily overflow!\\n    amount * rate\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_bps: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // Overflow before division\\n    (amount * fee_bps) / 10000\\n}\\n\\npub fn compound_interest(principal: u64, rate: u64, periods: u32) -> u64 {\\n    // Repeated multiplication causes overflow\\n    let mut result = principal;\\n    for _ in 0..periods {\\n        result = result * rate / 100;\\n    }\\n    result\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Checked multiplication\\npub fn convert_tokens(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    rate: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(rate)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    fee_bps: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_bps)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(10000))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\npub fn compound_interest(\\n    principal: u64,\\n    rate: u64,\\n    periods: u32,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let mut result = principal;\\n    \\n    for _ in 0..periods {\\n        result = result\\n            .checked_mul(rate)\\n            .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(100))\\n            .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    }\\n    \\n    Ok(result)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn calculate_token_amount(\\n    ctx: Context<CalculateAmount>,\\n    base_amount: u64,\\n    multiplier: u64,\\n) -> Result<u64> {\\n    base_amount\\n        .checked_mul(multiplier)\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Safe decimal conversion\\npub fn ui_to_raw_amount(\\n    ui_amount: u64,\\n    decimals: u8,\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    let power = 10_u64\\n        .checked_pow(decimals as u32)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::InvalidArgument)?;\\n    \\n    ui_amount\\n        .checked_mul(power)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-overflow", "https://docs.rs/solana-program/latest/solana_program/macro.checked_mul.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.958395+00	2025-11-29 01:51:09.978326+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-ACC-001	Controlled Library Call Vulnerability	Library calls using user-controlled class hashes allow attackers to redirect contract execution to malicious implementations. In Cairo/Starknet, library calls execute code from another contract's class using its class hash. If the class hash is derived from user input without validation, an attacker can supply a malicious contract's class hash, leading to arbitrary code execution within the calling contract's context.	access-control	high	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Always validate library call class hashes against a whitelist of approved contracts. Never derive class hashes directly from user input. Use hardcoded or admin-controlled class hashes for library calls.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: User-controlled library call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_library_call(ref self: ContractState, class_hash: ClassHash, selector: felt252) {\\n    library_call_syscall(class_hash, selector, array![].span()).unwrap();\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Whitelist validation\\n#[storage]\\nstruct Storage {\\n    approved_libraries: LegacyMap<ClassHash, bool>,\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn execute_library_call(ref self: ContractState, class_hash: ClassHash, selector: felt252) {\\n    assert(self.approved_libraries.read(class_hash), 'Unauthorized library');\\n    library_call_syscall(class_hash, selector, array![].span()).unwrap();\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Controlled Library Call"}, {"url": "https://docs.starknet.io/documentation/architecture_and_concepts/Smart_Contracts/class-hash/", "title": "Starknet Contract Classes"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.968854+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.00346+00	t
BVD-SOLIDITY-AUCTION-001	Auction Timing Manipulation	Auction timing vulnerabilities allowing manipulation of auction end times or bid timing	defi	medium	SWC-116	CWE-367	A4: Race Conditions	Use block numbers instead of timestamps where possible, implement anti-sniper mechanisms, add bid extension periods, and use commit-reveal for bids	["Extend auction time on late bids (anti-sniping)", "Use block numbers for time-based logic", "Implement commit-reveal bidding", "Add minimum time between bids"]	["https://consensys.github.io/smart-contract-best-practices/development-recommendations/solidity-specific/timestamp-dependence/"]	{static,manual}	0.25	{solidity}	Auction contracts vulnerable to timing manipulation or sniping attacks	{auction,timing,sniping,timestamp}	2025-11-29 01:17:01.675791+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.465791+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-QUA-004	Dead Code Detection	Private functions that are never called represent dead code that increases contract size, deployment costs, and maintenance burden. Dead code can also hide security vulnerabilities that might be triggered if the code is accidentally invoked in the future. Identifying and removing unused private functions helps keep contracts lean, secure, and maintainable.	code-quality	low	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Remove unused private functions to reduce contract size and complexity. If functions are kept for future use, document this decision clearly. Use code coverage tools to identify dead code. Regularly audit contracts to remove deprecated or unused functionality.", "code_example": "// PROBLEMATIC: Unused private function\\n#[generate_trait]\\nimpl InternalImpl of InternalTrait {\\n    fn _validate_signature(self: @ContractState, hash: felt252, signature: Span<felt252>) -> bool {\\n        // Complex signature validation logic that's never called\\n        true\\n    }\\n    \\n    fn _update_balance(ref self: ContractState, account: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n        self.balances.write(account, amount);\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn deposit(ref self: ContractState, amount: u256) {\\n    // Only calls _update_balance, _validate_signature is dead code\\n    self._update_balance(get_caller_address(), amount);\\n}\\n\\n// BETTER: Remove unused function\\n#[generate_trait]\\nimpl InternalImpl of InternalTrait {\\n    fn _update_balance(ref self: ContractState, account: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n        self.balances.write(account, amount);\\n    }\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Dead Code"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:26.017783+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.122928+00	t
