BVD-SOLANA-INT-003	Integer Division Precision Loss	Integer division operations that cause precision loss in financial calculations. In Rust, division of integers truncates the fractional part, which can lead to rounding errors in token amounts, fee calculations, or reward distributions. Repeated division operations can accumulate significant errors.	arithmetic	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "For financial calculations, perform multiplication before division to minimize precision loss. Consider using fixed-point arithmetic libraries or scaling factors. Document any intentional rounding behavior.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Division before multiplication\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_rate: u64) -> u64 {\\n    // If fee_rate is a percentage (e.g., 5 for 5%)\\n    // This loses precision!\\n    (amount / 100) * fee_rate\\n}\\n\\n// Example: amount = 999, fee_rate = 5\\n// Result: (999 / 100) * 5 = 9 * 5 = 45\\n// Expected: 999 * 0.05 = 49.95 \\u2248 49\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Multiple divisions\\npub fn distribute_rewards(total: u64, users: u64) -> u64 {\\n    let per_user = total / users;  // Precision loss\\n    let per_day = per_user / 30;   // More precision loss\\n    per_day\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Multiplication before division\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_rate: u64) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // Multiply first, then divide\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_rate)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(100))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// Example: amount = 999, fee_rate = 5\\n// Result: (999 * 5) / 100 = 4995 / 100 = 49 \\u2713\\n\\n// SECURE: Using basis points (1/10000)\\npub fn calculate_fee_basis_points(amount: u64, fee_bps: u64) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    // fee_bps in basis points (e.g., 500 = 5%)\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_bps)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(10000))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Fixed-point with scaling factor\\nconst SCALE: u64 = 1_000_000;  // 6 decimal places\\n\\npub fn calculate_scaled_amount(\\n    amount: u64,\\n    rate_scaled: u64,  // Rate pre-multiplied by SCALE\\n) -> Result<u64, ProgramError> {\\n    amount\\n        .checked_mul(rate_scaled)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(SCALE))\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with documented rounding\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn calculate_fee(amount: u64, fee_numerator: u64, fee_denominator: u64) -> Result<u64> {\\n    // Explicitly document rounding behavior\\n    let fee = amount\\n        .checked_mul(fee_numerator)\\n        .and_then(|v| v.checked_div(fee_denominator))\\n        .ok_or(error!(ErrorCode::ArithmeticOverflow))?;\\n    \\n    Ok(fee)  // Rounds down (floor division)\\n}"}	[]	["https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch03-02-data-types.html#integer-types", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/on-chain-programs/developing-rust#precision"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.90722+00	2025-11-29 01:51:09.88733+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-TYP-003	Enum Variant Confusion	Type confusion in enum deserialization where programs don't properly validate enum discriminants, allowing invalid or unexpected variants to be processed. In Borsh serialization, enums are prefixed with a variant index, but missing validation can allow out-of-range indices or mismatched variants.	type-safety	medium	\N	\N	A03:2021	{"description": "Use Rust's type system and Borsh's built-in validation. Avoid manual enum deserialization. Use match statements with explicit patterns and no wildcards for critical logic.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unsafe enum handling\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize)]\\npub enum InstructionType {\\n    Initialize = 0,\\n    Deposit = 1,\\n    Withdraw = 2,\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_instruction(\\n    instruction_data: &[u8],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Borsh deserializes any u8 into the enum\\n    // Value 255 would panic or create invalid variant\\n    let instruction_type = InstructionType::try_from_slice(instruction_data)?;\\n    \\n    // Wildcard catches invalid variants silently\\n    match instruction_type {\\n        InstructionType::Initialize => initialize()?,\\n        _ => {}\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Manual enum parsing\\npub fn parse_instruction_type(data: &[u8]) -> InstructionType {\\n    // No validation of variant value\\n    let variant = data[0];\\n    unsafe { std::mem::transmute::<u8, InstructionType>(variant) }\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Explicit variant matching\\n#[derive(BorshDeserialize, BorshSerialize, PartialEq, Debug)]\\npub enum InstructionType {\\n    Initialize,\\n    Deposit,\\n    Withdraw,\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_instruction(\\n    instruction_data: &[u8],\\n) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let instruction_type = InstructionType::try_from_slice(instruction_data)\\n        .map_err(|_| ProgramError::InvalidInstructionData)?;\\n    \\n    // Explicit match with no wildcards\\n    match instruction_type {\\n        InstructionType::Initialize => initialize()?,\\n        InstructionType::Deposit => deposit()?,\\n        InstructionType::Withdraw => withdraw()?,\\n        // Compiler ensures all variants handled\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor's instruction enum\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\n#[program]\\npub mod my_program {\\n    use super::*;\\n    \\n    pub fn initialize(ctx: Context<Initialize>) -> Result<()> {\\n        // Anchor validates instruction discriminator\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n    \\n    pub fn deposit(ctx: Context<Deposit>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n        // Each instruction has unique discriminator\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n    \\n    pub fn withdraw(ctx: Context<Withdraw>, amount: u64) -> Result<()> {\\n        Ok(())\\n    }\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Validated enum with Try trait\\nuse std::convert::TryFrom;\\n\\n#[derive(Debug, PartialEq)]\\npub enum TransactionStatus {\\n    Pending = 0,\\n    Completed = 1,\\n    Failed = 2,\\n}\\n\\nimpl TryFrom<u8> for TransactionStatus {\\n    type Error = ProgramError;\\n    \\n    fn try_from(value: u8) -> Result<Self, Self::Error> {\\n        match value {\\n            0 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Pending),\\n            1 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Completed),\\n            2 => Ok(TransactionStatus::Failed),\\n            _ => Err(ProgramError::InvalidArgument),\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_status(status_byte: u8) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let status = TransactionStatus::try_from(status_byte)?;\\n    // status is guaranteed to be valid variant\\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://borsh.io/", "https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch06-01-defining-an-enum.html"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.922917+00	2025-11-29 01:51:09.910184+00	t
BVD-SOLANA-LOG-001	Incorrect Loop Termination Logic	Loops with flawed break conditions, unreachable exits, or incorrect iteration logic that can cause infinite loops, incomplete processing, or incorrect state updates. In Solana programs with compute unit limits, infinite loops will exhaust the budget and cause transaction failure, but incorrect loop logic can also lead to partial state updates or skipped validation.	logic-errors	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Ensure loop conditions are correct and reachable. Use bounded loops with explicit limits. Validate loop invariants and ensure all items are processed correctly.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: Unreachable break condition\\npub fn process_items(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let mut i = 0;\\n    loop {\\n        if i >= items.len() {\\n            break;  // Correct condition\\n        }\\n        \\n        process_item(&items[i])?;\\n        \\n        // MISSING: i increment - infinite loop!\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Off-by-one error\\npub fn distribute_rewards(users: &mut [User], total: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let per_user = total / users.len() as u64;\\n    \\n    // Skips last user!\\n    for i in 0..users.len() - 1 {\\n        users[i].balance += per_user;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// VULNERABLE: Early break skips validation\\npub fn validate_accounts(accounts: &[AccountInfo]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    for account in accounts {\\n        if !account.is_signer {\\n            break;  // Should be 'continue' or 'return Err'\\n        }\\n        // Later accounts not validated!\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct loop with bounds\\npub fn process_items(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Use iterator with explicit bound\\n    for item in items.iter() {\\n        process_item(item)?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\npub fn process_items_indexed(items: &[Item]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    // Explicit iteration with correct bounds\\n    for i in 0..items.len() {\\n        process_item(&items[i])?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Correct distribution logic\\npub fn distribute_rewards(users: &mut [User], total: u64) -> ProgramResult {\\n    let user_count = users.len() as u64;\\n    require!(user_count > 0, ErrorCode::NoUsers);\\n    \\n    let per_user = total.checked_div(user_count)\\n        .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    \\n    // Process all users\\n    for user in users.iter_mut() {\\n        user.balance = user.balance\\n            .checked_add(per_user)\\n            .ok_or(ProgramError::ArithmeticOverflow)?;\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Complete validation\\npub fn validate_accounts(accounts: &[AccountInfo]) -> ProgramResult {\\n    for account in accounts {\\n        if !account.is_signer {\\n            return Err(ProgramError::MissingRequiredSignature);\\n        }\\n        // All accounts validated before continuing\\n    }\\n    Ok(())\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Using Anchor with bounded loops\\nuse anchor_lang::prelude::*;\\n\\npub fn process_batch(\\n    ctx: Context<ProcessBatch>,\\n    items: Vec<u64>,\\n) -> Result<()> {\\n    // Validate size limit\\n    const MAX_BATCH_SIZE: usize = 10;\\n    require!(\\n        items.len() <= MAX_BATCH_SIZE,\\n        ErrorCode::BatchTooLarge\\n    );\\n    \\n    // Process with guaranteed bound\\n    for item in items.iter() {\\n        process_item_safe(*item)?;\\n    }\\n    \\n    Ok(())\\n}"}	[]	["https://docs.solana.com/developing/programming-model/runtime#compute-budget", "https://docs.solana.com/developing/on-chain-programs/limitations#compute-budget"]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.933372+00	2025-11-29 01:51:09.924847+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-ARI-001	Felt252 Unsafe Arithmetic Operations	The felt252 type in Cairo is not overflow/underflow safe. Unlike u256 or u128, felt252 operations wrap around modulo the Cairo prime (2^251 + 17 * 2^192 + 1) without raising errors. When user-controlled values are used in felt252 arithmetic without bounds checking, attackers can exploit wraparound behavior to manipulate calculations, bypass validations, or drain funds.	arithmetic	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Use unsigned integer types (u8, u16, u32, u64, u128, u256) instead of felt252 for arithmetic operations. These types have built-in overflow/underflow checks. If felt252 is necessary, implement explicit bounds checking before operations. For financial calculations, always use u256 or implement safe math libraries.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: felt252 arithmetic without bounds checking\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: felt252) {\\n    let sender_balance: felt252 = self.balances.read(get_caller_address());\\n    // Subtraction can underflow, addition can overflow\\n    let new_sender_balance = sender_balance - amount;\\n    let recipient_balance = self.balances.read(recipient);\\n    let new_recipient_balance = recipient_balance + amount;\\n    \\n    self.balances.write(get_caller_address(), new_sender_balance);\\n    self.balances.write(recipient, new_recipient_balance);\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Use u256 with automatic checks\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn transfer(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    let sender = get_caller_address();\\n    let sender_balance: u256 = self.balances.read(sender);\\n    \\n    // These operations automatically check for overflow/underflow\\n    assert(sender_balance >= amount, 'Insufficient balance');\\n    self.balances.write(sender, sender_balance - amount);\\n    \\n    let recipient_balance = self.balances.read(recipient);\\n    self.balances.write(recipient, recipient_balance + amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Felt252 Unsafe Arithmetic"}, {"url": "https://oxor.io/blog/2024-08-16-overflow-and-underflow-vulnerabilities-in-cairo/", "title": "Cairo Overflow and Underflow Vulnerabilities"}, {"url": "https://book.cairo-lang.org/ch02-02-data-types.html", "title": "Cairo Field Elements"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.978579+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.024113+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-REE-002	Read-Only Reentrancy	Read-only reentrancy occurs in view functions that read storage variables that can be modified by external calls in other functions. When a view function reads state after an external call in a non-view function, it may return stale or inconsistent data. This can be exploited in DeFi protocols where price oracles, collateral ratios, or other critical values are queried while the contract is in an inconsistent state.	reentrancy	medium	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Implement reentrancy guards even for view functions that read critical state. Ensure state consistency before allowing external contracts to query values. Use snapshots or checkpoints for values that must remain consistent during execution. Consider using the OpenZeppelin ReentrancyGuard for all state-reading functions in sensitive contexts.", "code_example": "// VULNERABLE: View function reading inconsistent state\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_oracle(ref self: ContractState) {\\n    let old_price = self.price.read();\\n    // External call that could re-enter\\n    let new_price = IOracleDispatcher { contract_address: self.oracle.read() }\\n        .get_price();\\n    self.price.write(new_price);\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_collateral_ratio(self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    let price = self.price.read(); // May read stale price during reentrancy\\n    let collateral = self.collateral.read(user);\\n    collateral * price / PRECISION\\n}\\n\\n// SECURE: Reentrancy guard for state consistency\\nuse openzeppelin::security::reentrancyguard::ReentrancyGuardComponent;\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn update_oracle(ref self: ContractState) {\\n    self.reentrancy_guard.start();\\n    let old_price = self.price.read();\\n    let new_price = IOracleDispatcher { contract_address: self.oracle.read() }\\n        .get_price();\\n    self.price.write(new_price);\\n    self.reentrancy_guard.end();\\n}\\n\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn get_collateral_ratio(self: @ContractState, user: ContractAddress) -> u256 {\\n    assert(!self.reentrancy_guard.is_active(), 'Reentrancy detected');\\n    let price = self.price.read();\\n    let collateral = self.collateral.read(user);\\n    collateral * price / PRECISION\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Read-Only Reentrancy"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/immunefi/read-only-reentrancy-a-deep-dive-8ea3dbe5f275", "title": "Read-Only Reentrancy in DeFi"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.992446+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.087416+00	t
BVD-CAIRO-REE-003	Benign Reentrancy	Benign reentrancy occurs when a storage variable is written after an external call but was not read before it. While not immediately exploitable, benign reentrancy indicates potential issues with state consistency and can become critical if the code evolves to read the variable before the call. It also increases code complexity and makes future modifications more dangerous.	reentrancy	low	\N	\N	A04:2021	{"description": "Follow the checks-effects-interactions pattern consistently even when current code doesn't read the variable. Move all state updates before external calls. This prevents future modifications from inadvertently introducing vulnerabilities. Use reentrancy guards as a defense-in-depth measure.", "code_example": "// BENIGN BUT RISKY: State update after external call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn process_payment(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    // External call first\\n    IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: self.token.read() }\\n        .transfer(recipient, amount);\\n    \\n    // State update after (benign if not read before, but risky pattern)\\n    self.total_processed.write(self.total_processed.read() + amount);\\n}\\n\\n// BETTER: State update before external call\\n#[external(v0)]\\nfn process_payment(ref self: ContractState, recipient: ContractAddress, amount: u256) {\\n    // Update state first\\n    self.total_processed.write(self.total_processed.read() + amount);\\n    \\n    // External call after\\n    IERC20Dispatcher { contract_address: self.token.read() }\\n        .transfer(recipient, amount);\\n}"}	[]	[{"url": "https://github.com/crytic/caracal", "title": "Caracal - Benign Reentrancy"}]	{}	0	{}	\N	{}	2025-11-08 17:33:25.995417+00	2025-11-29 01:51:10.097089+00	t
